  <!-- WHY -->
  <section>
    <h2>Why projects are stalling</h2>
    <div class="section-rule"></div>
    <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem">Analysis from infrastructure lenders and energy market researchers has identified four structural problems with the CIS design that together explain the low FID conversion rate.</p>

    <div class="reasons-grid">
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-num">01</div>
        <div class="reason-title">The low-bid trap</div>
        <p class="reason-desc">Competitive auctions drive projects to bid the lowest possible revenue floor to win a contract. In many cases, the winning floor is below what equity investors require given current construction cost escalation — a classic "winner's curse." The project wins the contract but cannot attract finance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-num">02</div>
        <div class="reason-title">No price discovery</div>
        <p class="reason-desc">Winning floor prices are kept confidential. This means competing developers, lenders and equity investors have no way to assess whether existing CIS winners are viable or "zombie" projects, distorting the broader investment landscape and making it harder for genuinely viable projects to secure finance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-num">03</div>
        <div class="reason-title">Weak penalties for non-delivery</div>
        <p class="reason-desc">The scheme prioritises lowest-cost bids with limited financial consequences for projects that win contracts but never proceed to construction. This creates an incentive for speculative or premature bidding, allowing zombie projects to occupy contract space without consequence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-num">04</div>
        <div class="reason-title">The equity gap</div>
        <p class="reason-desc">A CISA alone is insufficient to attract equity investment. Lenders also question whether revenue floors justify project risk. Offtake agreements — like the EnergyAustralia deal that unlocked Orana BESS financing — are required but hard to negotiate, creating a chicken-and-egg problem.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr>

  <!-- OUTLOOK -->
  <section>
    <h2>What to watch in 2026</h2>
    <div class="section-rule"></div>
    <p>The critical metric for 2026 is Final Investment Decisions, not contract announcements. New contract awards generate press releases; FIDs generate construction jobs and actual megawatts on the grid.</p>
    <p>Given that large-scale wind and solar projects take 2–3 years from construction start to grid connection, any project that does not reach FID before mid-2026 will not contribute meaningfully to the 2030 renewable energy target. The window is closing.</p>
    <p>Two South Australian wind projects — Carmody's Hill and Willogoleche 2 — are the most likely near-term wind FIDs. In storage, Tender 3's two projects that already achieved FID (announced at contract award) demonstrate that the battery sector remains more bankable than generation.</p>
    <p>If the FID drought for generation projects persists past the second half of 2026, the government will face pressure for a structural review of the CIS — potentially pivoting toward a fixed-price Contract for Difference model similar to the ACT Government's successful long-form feed-in tariff, or introducing penalties for non-delivery to deter speculative bidding.</p>

